Who Are The Best Professional League of Legends Players?

Introduction

League of Legends (LoL) is a MOBA (Multiplayer Online Battle Arena) game developed by Riot Games. Released in 2009, LoL has rapidly grown in popularity, having become one of the most played multiplayer online games and most played electronic sport (e-sport) in the world. As of 2021 it boasts a global revenue of $15 billion USD, professional franchises and partnerships worth hundreds of millions of dollars, and 115 million active monthly users with over 150 million registered users. The premise of the game is relatively simple: Two teams of five players battle in player versus player combat, each team occupying and defending their half of the map. Each of the ten players controls a unique character with distinct abilities and differing styles of play. During a match, champions become more powerful by collecting experience points, earning gold, and purchasing items to defeat the opposing team. In the game a team wins by pushing through to the enemy base and destroying their "Nexus", a large structure located within. More information can be found here.

By Keman Wang

Motivation

In my tutorial, I am interested in shedding some light on who are considered the best professional League of Legends players, as well as finding out what factors make a player "good". As we have learned from the Moneyball story on the strength of utilizing data science in producing a strong baseball team, I believe this project can similarly represent good data science practices in order to create a similarly strong League of Legends e-sport team. While it may be relatively straightforward to conclude who are the best League of Legends players of each year by identifying the winners of each year's World Championship, perhaps there are other characteristics between players that could indicate factors which help make a team more likely to win. Data science practices help us in this regard by giving us tools to help identify player characterstics, clarity on how those characteristics might relate to player performance, and determine whether any particular element should be focused on when identifying and drafting professional players. For readers that are unfamiliar with the game, I hope this analysis will act as a gentle introduction into League of Legends and make them interested in trying out the game, as well as follow its professional scene as the game continues to take the world by storm. For experienced players and growing franchises, I hope to provide some insight on intriguing statistic correlations between the best League of Legends players, as well as help with drafting promising individual talents into fantasy teams or professional teams.

Data Collection and Preprocessing

With the conclusion of the 2020 League of Legends World Championship, we will be pulling the player statistics from every player that participated in the League of Legends World Championships from 2014-2020 from this website that hosts a plethora of player statistics for recreational fantasy team building.

We begin by manually extracting the data from the years of 2014-2020 from the JSON HTML web page URLS into 5 data frames which can be read more upon here. Manual scraping from the tables was not an option here due to the fact that the website generated the table through scripts. The unique URL for each JSON HTML were found by scrolling through the website source code in order to find the option values for each respective year. Note that we will be adding in an additional column representing year as it will help us analyze the data later.

In [2]:
# Obtaining 2014 League of Legends World Championship Data
r = requests.get("https://www.rotowire.com/esports/tables/stats-lol.php?type=total&league=297&series=4")
array = json.loads(r.content)
df2014 = pd.DataFrame()
for i in array:
    df2014 = df2014.append(i, ignore_index=True)
df2014['year'] = 2014

In the above example 2014 World Championship dataset there are 37 columns. We have:

  • ID (Unique player ID#)
  • Assists
  • CS (Creep score)
  • CSM (Creep score per minute)
  • Death Percentage (The percentage of deaths a player had in accordance with their team)
  • Deaths
  • DPM (Damage per minute to other players)
  • FB (Number of first kill of the game earned by player)
  • First Name
  • Gamertag (Unique player username)
  • Games (Number of games played)
  • Gold Percentage (The percentage of gold that a player gained for their team)
  • KDA (Kill/Death/Assist Ratio)
  • Kills
  • Kill Share Percentage (The number of the players kills divided by the number of team kills)
  • Kill Participation Percentage (The number of kills and assists divided by the number of team kills)
  • Last Name
  • Losses
  • Matches (Number of matches played)
  • Panda Team (Team Name)
  • Player (Player Full Name)
  • Player Damage (Total damage dealt to other players)
  • Player Gold (Total gold gained by the player)
  • Role (Position played by the player: Top, Mid, Jungle, Support, ADC)
  • Team (Secondary column for team name)
  • Team Damage (Total damage dealt to other players by the team)
  • Team Gold (Total gold earned by the team)
  • Team ID (Tertiary column for team name)
  • Team Kills (Total number of kills earned by the team)
  • Wards Cleared (Number of wards removed by player)
  • Wards Placed (Number of wards placed by player)
  • WCPM (Wards cleared per minute)
  • Wins
  • WPM (Wards placed per minute)
  • Year

The titles of each column here should also be self-explanatory. If you'd like to learn more about a column within the context of the game, important topics have links to additional information.

Data Tidying

As we can see above, there are many catagories above that are not needed as well as duplicate columns and rows containing essentially the same information, along with additional missing information that would be helpful later on during data analysis. For the sake of brevity we will be removing all columns involving player names and IDs, and will only be refering to players by their gamer tag from here on out.

Afterwards, we will be re-naming the Panda Team column to the team name column as the intial title name is confusing, as well as dropping the columns of 'team', 'teamID', 'matchLength', 'playerDam', 'playerGold', 'teamDam', 'teamDeaths', 'teamGold','teamKills' as they do not provide any useful or insightful information on the respective individuals in question. We will also be rearranging and renaming the columns of the dataframe for clarity. These changes will be applied to all dataframes along with an additional column being added identifying the winners of the world championship for each year which was found externally from here, which will be useful to us later during our data analysis.

Graphing Kill Death Assist Ratio vs. Win Ratio

Since Win Ratio is not calculated for us, we will calculate it ourselves by using this simple formula:
win ratio $= \frac{wins}{games played}$
We will then add these columns to each of the positional dataframes of each year. We do this because in the context of the game, kill-death-assist ratio and win ratio show us player performance averages rather than just a flat statistic that does not show the outcome of the games played. After doing so, we will plot the graph for each positional lane for years 2014-2020 to observe if there is any sort of relationship between K/D/A ratio and win ratio.

In [23]:
# Calculating win ratio for each positional dataframe for years 2014-2020
frames = [top2014,mid2014,jng2014,adc2014,sup2014,
          top2015,mid2015,jng2015,adc2015,sup2015,
          top2016,mid2016,jng2016,adc2016,sup2016,
          top2017,mid2017,jng2017,adc2017,sup2017,
          top2018,mid2018,jng2018,adc2018,sup2018,
          top2019,mid2019,jng2019,adc2019,sup2019,
          top2020,mid2020,jng2020,adc2020,sup2020]

# Iterate through list of dataframes and calculate a new win ratio column for each
for table in frames:
    table['winratio'] = pd.to_numeric(table['wins'])/pd.to_numeric(table['games'])
    
for table in frames:
    # Plot each positional dataframe for years 2014-2020
    table = table.sort_values(by='kda', ascending=True)
    sns.set_style('whitegrid')
    sns.lmplot(x='kda', y='winratio', data=table, fit_reg=False, palette=customPalette,
           hue='gamertag', height=5, aspect=2.5, legend=False)
    plt.legend(loc=9, bbox_to_anchor=(0.5, -0.2), ncol=5)
    plt.title('Kill-Death-Assist Ratio vs. Win Ratios for ' + table.iat[0,3] + ' Players in '
              +str(table.iat[0,0]) + ' World Championship')
    plt.xlabel('Kill-Death-Assist Ratio')
    plt.ylabel('Win Ratio')
    plt.show()

For all positional graphs throughout the years 2014-2020, it seems as if there is a positive relationship between getting more kills/assists than deaths and winning more often comparatively. While there are some datapoints throughout the graphs that show a relatively high win ratio compared to the player's low kill-death-assist ratio, which could lead us to surmise the possibility of particular in-game strategy which favors a passive playstyle and other external factors that may have affected the player's win ratio, a majority of the data points seem to fall within a linear growth model.

What is interesting to note is that for the year of 2014, despite the League of Legend's community praising the player Faker for his performace and multiple wins at the world stage, statistically speaking, PaWN was performing even better with a monsterous Kill-Death-Assist ratio of over 10.0 and a win percentage of over 70% during that year. Nevertheless, Faker did have an impressive consistent Kill-Death-Assist ratio of 7.3 with a win percentage of fluctuating between 91-70% throughout the multiple times he showed up to attend the World Championships, understandably earning him his moniker of the "Unkillable Demon King" throughout the League of Legends community as well as his reputation of being one of the best League of Legends players to play the game.

As for 2020 the statistics show that the best player in each respective role when factoring in Kill-Death-Assist Ratio and Win Ratio was Nuguri in the TOP position, ShowMaker in the MID position, Kongyue in the JNG position, Dee in the ADC position, and CoreJJ in the SUP position. This is quite a surprise as initially one would have assumed all positions would have been filled by players from the winning team for the World Championship of 2020.

Predicting Win Ratio

In this last section, we will focus on trying to build a model that can accurately predict the win percentage of a player based off their kill-death-assist ratio. There are a variety of prediction models that we could use, but due to the many different catagories of positions and player statistics, we will be using a linear regression model.

Linear Regression for Players

First in is bringing up the player statistics from the years of 2014-2020 throughout all positions. We will use the dfTotal dataframe created earlier on during our data preparation stage. We will drop everything except for the kill-death-assist column as well as add the win ratio column.

In [24]:
# Calculating win ratio column for dfTotal dataframe
dfTotal['winratio'] = pd.to_numeric(dfTotal['wins'])/pd.to_numeric(dfTotal['games'])
In [25]:
dfTotal = dfTotal.drop(['games','wins','losses','assists','kp','killshare','cs'
                        ,'csm','goldperc','dpm','fb','deathperc','wpm','wcpm','worldchamp'], axis = 1)
In [26]:
# Perform Linear Regression on Kill-Death-Assist Ratio
X = dfTotal.iloc[:,4].values.reshape(-1,1)
Y = dfTotal.iloc[:,5].values.reshape(-1,1)
reg = LinearRegression()
reg.fit(X,Y)
Ypred = reg.predict(X)

X = X.astype('float64')

#Visualize Results
sns.regplot(x=X,y=Y,line_kws={'color': 'red'})
plt.title('Linear Regression of Kill-Death-Assist Ratio vs. Win Ratios')
plt.xlabel('Kill-Death-Assist Ratio')
plt.ylabel('Win Ratio')
plt.show()

With these results we can clearly see that our hypothesis of a linear growth model was correct, as there is in fact a linear growth in regards to win ratio and kill-death-assist ratios, leading us to the conclusion that a majority of professional players that have attended the League of Legends World Championship have above a 1.0 Kill-Death-Assist Ratio and that the chances of winning do in fact rise based off increasing kill-death-assist statistics.

This falls in line with standard recruiting tactics as many franchises and fantatsy drafts often begin scouting for talent by anaylzing the player's previous performance history statistics and kill-death-assist ratio from previous years. What is interesting to note is that there are some outliers in the kill-death-assist ratios that lead to some intresting conclusions, as having more than a 15.0 kill-death-assist ratio does not seem to increase winning percentages. This leads to speculation on other potential factors and statstics that have a weighted impact on win ratios that kill-death-assist ratios do not reveal. This however, will be outside the scope of our data analysis.

Standardization of Win Ratios

Lastly, we will be doing an standardization of win ratios of all players througouth the years of the 2014-2020 World Championships to show the performance between all players that year. In order to standardize our data, we must show that the data is approximately normally distributed. Using seaborn, we can make violin plots of each year of data to make sure that the data is approximately normally distributed which can be read more about here.

In [27]:
sns.violinplot(x=dfTotal['year'], y=dfTotal['winratio'])
plt.title('Standardization of Win Ratios vs Year')
plt.xlabel('Years')
plt.ylabel('Win Ratio')
plt.show()

Great! The results fall within expectations of a normal distribution as they are unimodal violin graphs without too much skew to either and the mean of the plot (the white dot) lies approximately in the center of the distribution. While the win ratios of players seem to have dipped and risen again to around 0.5 one can speculate that the win ratio mean was at its lowest in 2017 due to the strong competitition that each team faced that year.
